metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #191
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Inland Emotions #193
metadata.description:
Inland Emotions

Over the centuries, ancient philosophers and modern psychologists have come to the same basic conclusion. The fact is that, according to a few millennia of research, there are a limited number of distinct human emotions, predefined by the human psyche. Sometimes it may seem like we are experiencing a "new" one, but on closer inspection, we see that it is the known emotions that are superimposed. Emotions are what they are, and they exist in the same way in each of us, whether we recognize them for what they are or not. But as our history blends into a new emerging state of the world, a whole new range of emotional responses are triggered within us. An infinite maelstrom of variations generated from a simple combination of a few emotions.


Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

Inland Emotions by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: BWEEPS  #41
metadata.description:
A minimalist, black-and-white generative profile picture (PFP) created to commemorate one-year anniversary of Bwople project by Gengoya. The artwork is derived from an initial sketch of Bwople which, despite being not the one that was chosen, still managed to captivate interests. The project provides a unique glimpse into an alternate universe in which Bwople could have been represented.

All images are hand-drawn work by Gengoya and composed by Vector Recite using PureSpider's fxhash-pfp maker tool.

To download the full size image on fx(hash):
- Click "open" below the image
- Left click on the image, a "Download image" button will appear on the bottom right.
- Click the "Download image" button.

metadata.name: Florescence #247
metadata.description:
Digitally crafted flowers in pots for virtual window sills.

In the spirit of the piranha plant from the Mario Bros videogame. We wanted to create a project that acknowledges the playful depiction of nature in early videogames by creating a retro futuristic collectible that explores aesthetics over gameplay, whilst preserving the playful energy of these early digital worlds. There are many game elements that have emerged over the years that have become iconic in their own right. Their memorable designs have come to represent the exciting feeling of when we first discovered these worlds, but over time an appreciation for their simple design execution, harmony and balance has emerged. Art can exist in many forms and places including a digital pot plant.

Rarity:

There are a total of 23 hand-drawn and animated sprites divided into 4 groups Firelillies, Flytraps, Quasars and Stargazers and there are 15 possible combinations made from these 4 groups. 18% of the collection is a combination of these 4 groups which we can call random and the remaining 72% is divided between the remaining 14 combinations.


There are 3 possible grid systems 1x1, 3x3 and 4x4 

3% 1x1

40% 3x3

57% 4x4



There are 14 possible placement points for all grids and 76 stem/sprite arragement in total



For the pots and stems there are 11 colors to choose and  no rarities for color combinations.



The flower distribution can be either symmetric or random. 35% symmetric and 65% random



Export options:

Pressing 's' on desktop or holding for 2 seconds will download gif to whatever the current device resolution is. To export at a different resolution open the token in new window by clicking 'open' link under the token image and add "&exportsize=1080" or "&exportsize=2160" to end of the url and hit enter then either hold for 2 seconds or press 's' to create gif and download.

metadata.name: Takashi's Death #74
metadata.description:
Akira by Katsuhiro Otomo.
A global landmark in the shaping of the Cyberpunk genre, and a watershed title for the medium.

I got my hands on the tankōbon(s) more than 20 years ago and those pages upon pages at the end of the third one depicting the destruction of Neo-Tokyo stayed with me ever since. Pages of stunning destruction, leaving me in awe.

This is my generative take on the subject. An attempt to evoke the power of that one panel in a cohesive collection.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more info on the composition here : https://ulucode.com/wp/takashis-death/

Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels ( height ). I recommend starting with "4".

More features are available, but a decent GPU is recommended:
- Press "space" to toggle an animation on/off
- Press "u" to Unlock the camera. You can then :
. Mouse left : Rotate
. Mouse middle/wheel : Zoom
. Mouse right : Translate
. "r" : reset camera
. "a" : change antialiasing quality : 3 settings in rotation. Try this if your framerate is too low.

metadata.name: LAND++ #11
metadata.description:
NOTE：
This work 《LAND++》 is a free mint work for collectors who own 《LAND》.
《LAND》 had a bug in it due to an error on my part, which caused the image to be blurred like an ink painting when displayed in Live View mode.
(This is a problem of misconfiguration of pixelDensity, and this problem can be avoided by setting the browser zoom size to 50% or less.)

This bug has been fixed in《LAND++》.
Thank you again to the collectors.

-----------------------------------------

It has been over a year since I released 《MOUNTAINS》 in 2023. In this work, while utilizing some of the same algorithms as 《MOUNTAINS》, we draw various landscapes with a simple code of less than 200 lines. By applying FLUX processing to geometric forms, we give a certain kind of gravity to the shapes.
Fertile lands, rugged terrains, desolate fields, and scorched earth（焼け野原） are generated.

1920×1080 px
p5js

Mar.8.2024

metadata.name: Kinetograms #402
metadata.description:
Each Kinetogram traces the movement of a number of simple shapes constrained within a single cell or a grid of cells. Forces are applied to the shapes in the form of attraction, gravity or shaking.

Some Kinetograms are partially or completely reflected, vertically or horizontally, some with chromatic replacement.

The aspect ratio is 3:4. The palettes are predominantly based on found textile patterns.

Press 's' to save a png image. Press 'e' to redraw and export a 4K png image. Note that drawing and physical simulation takes some time.

For interactive use, press 't' to tilt the board and 'c' to clear the board.

Written in p5.js with 2D physical simulation using Matter.js. Developed in and optimized for Chrome.

objkt.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #193

metadata.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #193
metadata.description:
Experimental generative collection that merges analog photography, AI, generative text, and algorithmic coding, by digging down into the essence and building blocks of the different artistic communication channels. 

This work engages with all aforementioned mediums in a joint manner, guided by a random process. It starts with a collection of analog photographs, shot on film and scanned that were later used as a training dataset in Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) training. This way, A.I. learns the main characteristics of film photography. In particular, it mimics its recognizable grain. Another type of pixel grain is added with the use of code and pixel shifting as well as digital manipulation. Finally, the last type of “grain” appears with the use of generative text where a different kind of A.I. was given a short description of the project and instructed to imagine the rest of the story. The fragmented and void of meaning parts of generative text are added to the images as one of the possible traits.

metadata.name: Vorticity #49
metadata.description:
Vorticity is a gpu-accelerated flow field. The particles in the flow field orbit around a set of points that move around over time.

Controls: Click and drag to push particles away. Press the space bar to pause the simulation, and again to resume. While paused, you can press "n" to advance the simulation a single step. Press "r" to restart the simulation (if you change the resolution of the screen after the page loads, you will need to restart to update the resolution).

metadata.name: tur1ng #8
metadata.description:
‘tur1ng’ consists of audible image architectures based on the principle of Turing machines. These systems are mathematical models of computation that manipulate symbols on a strip of tape according to a table of rules. The machine first writes a symbol in a cell on the tape, then either moves the tape one cell left or right, then, based on the observed symbol and the machine's own state in the table, either proceeds to another instruction or halts computation.

In ‘tur1ng’, rules are stored as colors and the original tape cells are constructed from a two dimensional array. The sound unfolds as the algorithm proceeds: monitoring these binary songs requires being attentive to changes in the state or behavior of the system over time so that appropriate interventions or other process-related activities may be carried out. Another feature of listening algorithms is that it often has to be done as a background or secondary task or, perhaps, in parallel with one or more other primary tasks.

Touch to listen.

metadata.name: Ascension #46
metadata.description:
The algorithmic kernel of this piece is a randomly perturbed, faceted ground plane. An emergent root system forms, spiraling inward along the ground plane's undulated facets toward a central randomized scaffold. Roots and eventually tendrils climb the scaffold, ascending to the sky.
